Yes, you can keep your existing checks and mostly keep your existing asset names/references.

The thing you cannot keep unchanged** is any asset artifact that is amd64-only and needs to execute on Graviton/ARM64.

Sensu supports dynamic runtime assets with multiple builds under the same asset definition, selected by filters such as entity.system.arch == 'amd64' or entity.system.arch == 'arm64'. Sensu’s docs explicitly show assets with separate linux_amd64 and linux_arm64 builds under the same asset, and note that filters determine which build is downloaded and installed. 

Best approach: keep check names and asset names the same

Do not change your checks like this:

runtime_assets:
  - check-cpu-usage-arm64

Instead, keep this unchanged:

runtime_assets:
  - check-cpu-usage

Then update the existing Asset named check-cpu-usage to include both builds:

type: Asset
api_version: core/v2
metadata:
  name: check-cpu-usage
  namespace: default
spec:
  builds:
    - url: https://your-artifact-store/check-cpu-usage_linux_amd64.tar.gz
      sha512: <amd64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

    - url: https://your-artifact-store/check-cpu-usage_linux_arm64.tar.gz
      sha512: <arm64-sha512>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

That way:

Check definition: unchanged
runtime_assets value: unchanged
Asset metadata.name: unchanged
Only Asset builds: updated

This is the safest GitOps migration pattern.

Important point

If your asset currently looks like this:

spec:
  url: https://your-artifact-store/plugin_linux_amd64.tar.gz
  sha512: <sha>
  filters:
    - entity.system.os == 'linux'
    - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

convert it to multi-build format:

spec:
  builds:
    - url: https://your-artifact-store/plugin_linux_amd64.tar.gz
      sha512: <amd64-sha>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'amd64'

    - url: https://your-artifact-store/plugin_linux_arm64.tar.gz
      sha512: <arm64-sha>
      filters:
        - entity.system.os == 'linux'
        - entity.system.arch == 'arm64'

Sensu docs say single-build assets using top-level url and sha512 are deprecated, and recommend spec.builds for one or more builds. 

What this means for your migration

You have two separate things to migrate:

1. Sensu container image

You need an ARM64-capable Sensu backend/agent image.

If you want the lowest-risk migration, do not upgrade Sensu and architecture at the same time. Ideally, use the same Sensu version you run today, but with an ARM64 or multi-arch image.

So instead of immediately jumping to:

sensu/sensu:6.11.0

I would first ask:

What Sensu version are you running today?

Then use that same version if an ARM64 image/build exists.

Sensu’s platform docs list ARM64/aarch64 support for the Sensu backend and show Linux arm64 binary distributions that include the agent, backend, and sensuctl. 

2. Existing Sensu assets

Your checks can remain the same, but every referenced asset must support ARM64 if it will run on ARM nodes.

Audit your Git repo:

grep -R "runtime_assets" ./sensu
grep -R "entity.system.arch" ./sensu
grep -R "amd64" ./sensu
grep -R "url:" ./sensu/assets

For every asset used by checks, handlers, filters, or mutators, confirm one of these:

It already has a linux_arm64 build
It is a script-only asset and works on ARM64
You can rebuild it for ARM64
You will temporarily keep that workload on AMD64

Phased migration I recommend

Phase 1 — keep checks/assets logically unchanged

Update only the asset definitions to add ARM64 builds under the same names.

No check changes.

Phase 2 — move Sensu backend to Graviton

This mainly affects:

handlers
filters
mutators
backend-side assets

If handlers use assets, those assets must support ARM64.

Phase 3 — move Sensu agents to Graviton

This affects:

checks
check runtime_assets
local scripts/binaries

This is where most asset failures show up.

ArgoCD/Kustomize-safe pattern

In your STG overlay:

overlays/stg/
  kustomization.yaml
  patches/
    sensu-image-arm64.yaml
    sensu-backend-graviton-scheduling.yaml
    sensu-agent-graviton-scheduling.yaml
    sensu-assets-arm64.yaml

Keep check YAMLs unchanged unless absolutely required.

For scheduling:

nodeSelector:
  kubernetes.io/arch: arm64

tolerations:
  - key: graviton
    operator: Equal
    value: "true"
    effect: NoSchedule

My recommendation

Do not change your check definitions.

Do not rename your assets.

Do this instead:

Keep existing checks
Keep existing asset names
Convert each asset to multi-build format
Add linux/arm64 asset build beside existing linux/amd64 build
Use same Sensu version if possible, but with ARM64-capable image
Move backend first, then agents

So the answer is: yes, you can keep your existing checks and assets from a GitOps/config point of view — but any amd64-only asset artifact must either get an ARM64 build or stay running on AMD64 nodes.